snippet.textDisplay:
Wilder started out with as noble a quest as can exist. Giving his all for his children.
He was blessed with an unusual capability that allowed him to rise to incredible heights of accomplishment.

Somewhere along the way, however, he became pompous and started to buy into his own hype.
His handlers and sycophantic fan base actually served him in ill fashion. He became a bully and even touted the fact that he had disregarded cultivating true boxing skills. Hubris on a collision course with Nemesis
He even started making it about race. Close scrutiny of his fights show that he was lacking in fundamental skills and open to a lot of blows. He was fallible as is any human being. He just hadn't met his real nemesis to counter his extreme and bloated pride.

Enter Tyson fury; a man who also fights for pride, honor and family, but who is also quite aware of his faults and shortcomings. A very large man with an impressive record of his own, he , as opposed to Wilder, cultivated myriad boxing skills from an early age. As happened with Liston / Ali, the end of the bully's reign was inevitable.

In defeat Wilder has proven less than genuine even to himself and can't come to grips with the fact that he actually brought this defeat unto himself. instead he seeks blame every place imaginable.
His was a good run. He must go back, try to hone his craft. He would be less than wise if he opted for an immediate rubber match with Fury
